#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:2
msgid "How to use custom environment variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:4
msgid ""
"If extra environment variables are needed in the build process, you can "
"define them from the project's :term:`dashboard`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:9
msgid ":doc:`/environment-variables`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:10
msgid ""
"Learn more about how Read the Docs applies environment variables in your "
"builds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:12
msgid ""
"Go to your project's :menuselection:`Admin --> Environment Variables` and "
"click on :guilabel:`Add Environment Variable`. You will then see the form "
"for adding an environment variable:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:15
msgid "Screenshot of the form for adding an environment variable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:18
msgid ""
"Fill in the :guilabel:`Name` field, this is the name of your variable, for "
"instance ``SECRET_TOKEN`` or ``PIP_EXTRA_INDEX_URL``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:19
msgid ""
"Fill in the :guilabel:`Value` field with the environment variable's value, "
"for instance a secret token or a build configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:20
msgid ""
"Check the :guilabel:`Public` option if you want to expose this environment "
"variable to :doc:`builds from pull requests </pull-requests>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:25
msgid ""
"If you make your environment variable **public**, any user that can create a "
"pull request on your repository will be able to see the value of this "
"environment variable. In other words, **do not use this option if your "
"environment variable is a secret.**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:30
msgid ""
"Finally, click on :guilabel:`Save`. Your custom environment variable is "
"immediately active for all future builds and you are ready to start using it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:34
msgid ""
"Note that once you create an environment variable, you won't be able to edit "
"or view its value. The only way to edit an environment variable is to delete "
"and create it again."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:38
msgid "Keep reading for a few examples of using environment variables. ⬇️"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:41
msgid "Accessing environment variables in code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:43
msgid ""
"After adding an environment variable, you can read it from your build "
"process, for example in your Sphinx's configuration file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:47
msgid "conf.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:47
msgid ""
"import os\n"
"import requests\n"
"\n"
"# Access to our custom environment variables\n"
"username = os.environ.get(\"USERNAME\")\n"
"password = os.environ.get(\"PASSWORD\")\n"
"\n"
"# Request a username/password protected URL\n"
"response = requests.get(\n"
"    \"https://httpbin.org/basic-auth/username/password\",\n"
"    auth=(username, password),\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:64
msgid "Accessing environment variables in build commands"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:66
msgid ""
"You can also use any of these variables from :term:`user-defined build jobs` "
"in your project's configuration file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:68
msgid ".readthedocs.yaml"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/environment-variables.rst:68
msgid ""
"version: 2\n"
"build:\n"
"  os: ubuntu-22.04\n"
"  tools:\n"
"    python: 3.10\n"
"  jobs:\n"
"    post_install:\n"
"      - curl -u ${USERNAME}:${PASSWORD} https://httpbin.org/basic-auth/"
"username/password"
msgstr ""

